<p><font size=5.4">
   Most antivirus programs would be better described as 'anti-malware's
   since they are often designed to protect against worms, Trojans and other types
   of malicious code.</font></p>
   <p><font size=5.4">
There are also antiviruses designed for browser security.
   It’s possible for malware, hackers and other cyber criminals to exploit weaknesses in web browsers.
    The major <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_browser">Web Browsers</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Chrome">Google Chrome</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Firefox">Firefox</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opera">Opera</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Safari">Safari</a>) also include a number of other security features, such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pop-up_ad">pop-up blockers</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phishing">phishing</a> detectors,
    which can warn you if a website appears to be a fraud.</font></p>
    <p><font size="5.4">
      Firewall is the first protection layer of your device against unauthorized access to your PC.
      It works in the background all the time monitoring traffic to (and, in some cases, from) your computer
      and blocks certain ports while allows specific programs and services to communicate with your PC.</font></p>

      <p><font size="5.4">
        Protecting from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phishing">phishing</a> frauds  takes a two-pronged effort, with anti-spam software filtering out unsolicited emails and web browser security features protecting against known fraudulent sites.</font></p>

   <p><font size="5.4">
Last but not least there exists an anti-spam software, which blocks unwanted or unsolicited email from reaching
 your email's inbox.</font></p>
